\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Designing for Effectiveness and Inclusivity in ICT-enabled Agricultural
 Extension: Evidence from Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bjorn Van Campenhout, Els Lecoutere, and David J Spielman
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In programs to disseminate information through agricultural extension and
 advisory services, seemingly small design attributes—the way the information
 is delivered, who delivers the information, or who is targeted by the message—c
an result in significant differences in the intervention's effectiveness
 and inclusiveness.
 Information and communications technology (ICT) can reduce the costs associated
 with adapting design attributes to particular problems and contexts.
 This study compares the effectiveness of different ICT-enabled technologies
 in providing agricultural extension services to smallholder farmers.
 In addition, it assesses the extent to which gender inclusivity in extension
 service provision can be influence by the gender composition of the person(s)
 who provide(s) the information and the gender composition of the person(s)
 who receive(s) the information in an ICT-enabled approach.
 Our study relies on a field experiment conducted among smallholder maize
 farmers in Uganda.
 The effectiveness of changing key design attributes—ICT technology, messenger,
 and recipient—is assessed by measuring knowledge gained, adoption of modern
 inputs and recommend practices, maize production and disposal, and well-being.
 The inclusivity of changing key design attributes is assessed by examining
 gender-disaggregated outcomes such as adoption and production on male-,
 female-, and jointly-managed plots, as well as intra-household decision-making.
 We find that short video-based extension messages increase knowledge, technolog
y adoption, and production at the household level.
 We find that a technology that is more demand driven further increases
 productivity, as farmers use it to obtain additional information on more
 complex technologies such as hybrid seed.
 Showing extension videos to both men and women (instead of only to men)
 increases women's knowledge, boosting their confidence and leading to more
 consultation among spouses.
 If women receive information, they make decisions (and adopt recommended
 technologies) on more plots, significantly increasing their role in maize
 production.
 However, this effect disappears if men also receive this information.
 Changing the messenger attribute does not have any effect on outcomes.
\end_layout

