 Besides, most agronomic information campaigns ignore the existence information
 assymetries within smallholder farm households and the fact that these
 households are composed of multiple decision makers with their own preferences,
 and typically target one person in the household, in many cases the male
 household head.
 As such, agricultural extension programs and advisory services—often provided
 as a public service—are viewed as necessary to improving agricultural outcomes,
 especially in developing countries.
 Yet outcomes of many extension efforts are mixed at best, and gender differentiated

