\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With new possibilities offered by information and communications technology
 (ICT), an abundance of pilot projects and commercial products have entered
 the market with a focus on revitalizing agricultural extension in developing
 countries.
 However, a growing body of evidence suggests that not all ICT-mediated
 extension approaches are equally effective in achieving outcomes such as
 increased rates of technology adoption, and higher crop yields of man and
 woman farmers, or improvements in household welfare and intra-household
 equity.
 This may be because, as has been found in information campaigns more generally,
 seemingly small design attributes—the way information is delivered, who
 delivers the information, and who was targeted—can significantly influence
 these outcomes.

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

This paper investigates the effectiveness and inclusivity of an ICT-enabled
 extension approach designed to provide information about improved maize
 cultivation practices to smallholder farmers in Uganda.
 In a first part of the paper, we consider the specific ICTs through which
 the information is delivered to the farmer, and differentiate between (i)
 short audiovisual messages viewed on tablet computers that provide detailed
 inromation on improved maize cultivation; (ii) interactive voice response
 (IVR) systems that farms call into if the need for additional information
 arises; and (iii) short message service (SMS) that nudge farmers at particular
 points in time about key farming practices they should apply.
 The outcomes used to assess the relative effectiveness of these different
 ICTs include increases in knowledge about improved maize cultivation by
 the subject farmer; and changes in household-level indicators such as the
 use of improved inputs, technologies, and practices; farm production and
 disposal; and well-being, all measured at the household level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In a second part of the paper, we explore the role and importance of gender-rela
ted attributes in the design of the ICT-mediated approach, focusing on (i)
 the gender composition of the recipient(s) of the information, and (ii)
 the gender composition of the messenger(s) providing the information.
 Experimental variations in these attributes allow us to assess the inclusivity
 of design attributes in extension provison.
 Specifically, we test hypotheses related to the influence of videos on
 information asymmetries within (dual) households, and the effectiveness
 of videos in changing certain customs, beliefs or gender stereotypes related
 to maize farming 

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A dual household is defined as a household containing both one male and
 one female member who take decisions as head of household either jointly
 or singly in their respective spheres of responsibility.
 It thus excludes single headed households or polygamous households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These gender-related outcomes are similarly assessed by examining knowledge
 gained at the individual level and the use of improved inputs, technologies,
 and practices at the household level, but also by examining changes in
 household decision-making processes and production outcomes on plots under
 male, female, and joint management.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

The hypothesis testing and outcome estimations described above draw on a
 field experiment in which farmers were randomly assigned to a group that
 received a particular ICT-mediated information, and were then compared
 to a group that did not receive that particular information intervention
 

\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2016field"

\end_inset

.
 Because we want to test more than one research hypothesis and are particularly
 interested in comparing the relative effectiveness of various design elements
 in an ICT-enabled extension approach, we opt for a factorial design.
 Generally, in factorial designs, a smaller sample size is needed to answer
 a fixed number of research questions as opposed to parallel designs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We work with 3,600 farm households sampled from the population of dual household
s cultivating maize across five districts of eastern Uganda.
 The core information interventions take the form of short videos that explain
 simple yet effective ways to increase maize productivity and profitability,
 such as recommended practices in row spacing, the importance of quality
 seed, optimal soil fertility management, and farm budget management.
 To test the overall effectiveness of the information provided through the
 video medium, we compare outcomes of farmers who were exposed to a placebo
 video to outcomes of farmers who were shown the informational video.
 In addition, we provided access to an IVR system to about two-thirds of
 the sampled households who were shown the informational video and, within
 that group, we sent about half of the sampled households a series of eight
 follow-up SMS messages at strategic points in time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

To test how information asymmetries within the household affects decision-making
 and outcomes, we compare households where the video was shown only to the
 man in the household (the status quo) to households where the video was
 shown to the woman alone in the household, and to households where the
 video was shown to the man and women together as a couple.
 To test the hypothesis on the importance of the gender (composition) of
 the person(s) providing the information, we produced different versions
 of the video.
 In each version of the video, the information content was exactly the same,
 only the person (or persons) featured in the video was changed.
 In one version of the video, all the information was provided by an individual
 male farmer; in a second version, the information was given by an individual
 female farmer; and in a third version, the information was given by a couple,
 with each spouse taking turns in the narration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

At the farm household level, we find that providing information to farmers through
 short video messages increases their knowledge about modern inputs, improved
 technologies, and recommended practices.
 In addition, farmers who were shown the video are also more likely to adopt
 a range of inputs, technologies, and practices that were presented in the
 videos.
 We also find clear effects on production with maize yields 14 percent higher
 than in control households.
 However, these results do not translate into greater well-being.
 We also find that the IVR generates no additional impact on knowledge,
 nor does it have a strong influence on technology adoption: we only find
 a positive effect of IVR on the uptake of hybrid seed.
 Still, we do find that households that were allocated to the IVR treatment
 report yields that are 8 percent higher.
 We also find no effect from the SMS service.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

With respect to who in the household receives the video message, there are
 few household-level effects.
 However, household-level effects may mask opposite effects at the individual
 level.
 We find that if the video is shown to the couple or to the woman (as opposed
 to only the man), knowledge of the woman increases significantly, suggesting
 information does not flow efficiently from the man to the woman within
 the household.
 When the video is shown to couple (as opposed to only the man), women are
 more likely to speak up if they do not agree, and it is more likely that
 an agreement is reached within the housheold.
 If women also receive information, men are less likely to make adoption
 decisions by themselves.
 Women, on the other hand, will make significantly more decisions on the
 use of improved agronomic practices and inputs, but only if this information
 is not also available to the husband.
 If only women receive information, they adopt more than if only men receive
 the information.

 As a result, we find that including women in this ICT-enabled extension
 approach increases the role of women in maize production.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, with respect to who the messenger is in the video, we do not find
 no significant effects.
 This implies that it does not matter if the information in the video was
 provided by a man, a woman, or a man and woman together.

\end_layout

