\begin_layout Subsection*
Impact of the gender attributes in the video intervention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

In this part of the paper we present results of the two gender-related attribute
s of the video intervention.
 The first attribute relates to the gender of the targeted audience: because
 extension services typically target men within households, we investigate
 the consequences of (additionally) targeting the female co-head of household.
 In particular, we report results for two comparisons: R1, which compares
 outcomes for households where the video was shown to the male co-head only
 to outcomes for households where the video was shown to the female co-head
 only; and R2, which compares outcomes for households where the video was
 shown to the male co-head only to households where the video was shown
 to both spouses together.
 The second attribute is related to the gender of the person that provides
 the information: because extension services typically employ male extension
 agents, we investigate the consequences of changing the messenger in the
 video to female, or at least adding a female messenger alongside the male
 messenger.
 We report results for two comparisons: M1, which compares outcomes for
 households where the version of the video shown features only a man providing
 the information to households where the version of the video shown features
 a woman only; and M2, which compares outcomes for households where the
 version of the video shown features a man only to households where the
 version of the video features a couple.
 We look at outcomes both at the household and individual levels, and pay
 particular attention to the impact on intra-household decision-making.
 
