 To some extent, the reduction in male decision-making about maize management
 as a result of the more inclusive extension approach is mirrored in an
 increase in decision-making by women within the household.
 However, even after the increase in women's decision-making when they are
 shown a video, women are still far less likely than men to decided about
 adoption of technologies, practices, and inputs on an average plot.
 For instance, based on the female decision index, when the male co-head
 is shown the video individually, women report they make adoption decisions
 on only 27 percent of plots.
 This percentage increases to 38 percent if the video is shown to the female
 co-head alone.
 However, this is still significantly lower than the 53 percent of plots
 man unilaterally decide on when they are provided information.
 Female decision-making also generally increases if the video is shown to
 a couple instead of only to the men, but the differences are generally
 not significant.
 We can thus conclude that if women also receive information, they will
 make significantly more decisions on the use of improved maize technologies,
 practices, and inputs, but only if this information is not also available
 to the husband.
 
